orskov, Denmark","Ejby Sogn, Ramsø Herred, Roskilde Amt, Danmark":"Ejby, Ramsø, Roskilde, Denmark","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plate","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Gunther, Hans, Heinz, Otto, Reinold.","German and Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a maker of plate armor, from Middle High German <i>blate</i>, <i>plate</i>, Middle Dutch <i>plate</i> ‘plate, armor plating’.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>plate</i> ‘sandbank at a river or in the sea’; also habitational name from a place so named in Mecklenburg and other regions."],"variants":[{"name":"Platte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Erwin, Franz, Hans, Kurt.","German: variant of   Plate   1.","German: topographic name for someone who lived on higher ground, from Middle Low German, Middle High German <i>plate</i> ‘(stone) plateau, rock wall’."]},{"name":"Platt","meanings":["English: Middle English <i>plat</i>, <i>platte</i> ‘flat surface’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>plat</i>, <i>plast</i>), often with the senses ‘footbridge’ or ‘plot of land’. The name may be topographic, for one who lived near such a feature, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Platt in Manchester or Platt Bridge in Wigan (both Lancashire).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname from German <i>platt</i> ‘flat’.","German: variant of   Platte   3."]}]},{"name":"Margrethe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353273,"age":23,"year":"1350","julianDay":2214138,"description":"Plague ravishes Denmark and Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Margrethe Clausdatter Plate was born about 1327, in Ejby, Ramsø, Roskilde, Denmark, her father, Claus Plate, was 20 and her mother, Von Segebande, was 21. She married Conrad Moltke til Bjernede about 1345. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1393."},"et":{"about 1327–Aft 1393":"umbes 1327–pärast 1393","1327–1393":"1327–1393","1327–1390":"1327–1390","1350–1391":"1350–1391","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1309–1358":"1309–1358","1308–Female":"1308–Surnud","nach 3. Dezember 1391":"pärast 3. detsembrit 1391","før 14. april 1390":"enne 14. aprilli 1390","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1327":"1327","1358":"1358","about 1327":"umbes 1327","1355":"1355","about 1358":"umbes 1358","about 1345":"umbes 1345","Aft 1393":"pärast 1393","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1309":"1309","1308":"1308","Omkr. 1350":"umbes 1350","Bjernede, Sorø, Danmark":"Bjernede, Sorø, Taani",", Antvorskov, Soro, Denmark":"Antvorskov, Antvorskov, Taani","Ejby Sogn, Ramsø Herred, Roskil